<taxonomicName authority="(Krauss, 1848)" baseAuthorityName="Krauss" baseAuthorityYear="1848" box="[424,841,557,581]" class="Bivalvia" family="Mytilidae" genus="Modiolus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mytilida" pageId="10" pageNumber="3238" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="auriculatus">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[424,661,557,581]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="3238">Modiolus auriculatus</emphasis>
(Krauss, 1848)
</taxonomicName>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[154,1110,621,711]" pageId="10" pageNumber="3238">
<emphasis box="[194,288,622,646]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="3238">Habitat.</emphasis>
Attached by a byssus, mostly in sand and rubble mixtures but also in crevices and holes. Forms rafts on sand-covered rocks on the exposed north and east coasts. Frequently heavily encrusted by macroalgae.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="3238" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="10.[154,1111,723,812]" pageId="10" pageNumber="3238">
<emphasis box="[194,335,723,747]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="3238">Distribution.</emphasis>
Throughout the lagoon from low in the intertidal to a few metres around the reef edge. Large densities occur along the more exposed eastern areas, notably at Pointe Coton.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
